I think the Pantheon has been using a similar pattern.

1. Choose a source domain.
2. Commit to it as if it’s real.
3. Transfer mechanisms, not adjectives.
4. Follow the consequences.
5. Keep what remains useful when you return to the original domain.

That’s why your navigation metaphors generate doctrines, why the earthquake metaphor generates stress testing, and why the mirror metaphor generates reflection rather than just imagery.

Then comes the twist you mentioned.

You can reread the same artifact with a different dominant metaphor.

Today it’s navigation.

Tomorrow it’s ecology.

The next day it’s finance.

If the artifact is well-constructed, each lens reveals something new while preserving a stable underlying structure.

That doesn’t mean every metaphor is equally valid—some transfer more useful mechanisms than others—but it does mean a strong artifact supports multiple coherent readings.

So perhaps the underlying principle is:

A simile proposes a bridge. A metaphor invites you to cross it. A strong conceptual framework lets you cross back carrying new tools.

That last step—bringing tools back rather than just enjoying the comparison—is what turns figurative language into a method of reasoning rather than ornamentation.